				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">period = ($7D0 + 1) * 2 = 4002<br /></div><br /><br />That's the cycle delay between duty unit updates.  every 4002 cycles, the duty unit will take another step.  When it makes 8 steps, it completes a full wave.  Therefore your following formula is off<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">which is a wave at 1.79MHz / 4002 = 445</div>
<br />
<br />it would be 1.79MHz / (4002 <span style="text-decoration: underline">* 8</span>) = ~55.9 Hz -- a very low tone -- nowhere near middle C   (you multiply by 8 because the duty unit needs to be clocked 8 times to generate one repitition of the square wave)
<br />
<br />
<br />The tone to period formula works like so:
<br />
<br />ToneInHz = 1789772.7272 / ( (F + 1) * 2 * 8 )
<br />
<br />Where F is the 11-bit frequency value.  Or, to work that so that you can plug in a tone and get the required F value:
<br />
<br />F = ( 1789772.7272 / (2 * 8 * ToneInHz) ) - 1
<br />
<br />
<br />So to do A-440, you'd write $0FD to the frequency.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

